OSLO, Norway DR.. Martin
Luther King accepted the 1864
Nobel peace prize "in behalf
Of a civil rights movement which
Is moving with determination
and ma estic scorn for risk
and danger to establish a reign
Of freedom and rule Of Jus
tiee!"


The American civil rights
leader, 55, youngest ever to re-
eeive the Nobel laurel, was given
a standing ovation led by King
OiaV and Crown Prince HaFald.


The award Ii a gold medal and
$50 900 In cash value.


In his acceptance speech, Dr..
King declared, "Bven though mo-
dern man has reached new and
astonishing peaks Of scientific
success, something basic Ii
missing. There IL a sort Of po-
verify Of the spirit which stands
In glaring contrast to our seien-

The richer we have become ma

Prior to his arrival In Oslo to
accept the Nobel Prize, DR.. King
was guest minister on Sunday at
the famous St. Paurs Cathedral
in London. He was the first
black man to speak from the pull
pit of that historic church.

The National Council of Negro
Women will hold its first Flea
nor Roosevelt-Mary Mcleod
Bethune World Citizenship
Awards Dinner on Dec. y in
the Grand Ballroom of the Wal
dorf Astoria.


Mrs. Hubert H. Humphrey
as been invited as guest of
honor.


With the dinner there will be an
International Debutante Citizen
ship Cotillion. Young women of
various races and countries, Sc
lected for their citizenship &C
tivities during the year, will be
presented.


Mayor Wagner is honorary
chairman for the event. The CO.
chairmen are Mrs. John Mos
Ter, Mrs. Charles Buchanan and
Mrs. Arthur Logan.


Proceeds from the dinner and
cotillion will go toward the COM
pletion of the Mary Mcleod
Bethune Memorial in Washing
ton.

gro Women is the coordinating
agency for Is organizations with
a total membership of nearly
four million women.
